ggplo2 Basics

Background

ggplot2 is one of the most widely used packages in all of R! It was created by Hadley Wickham, a very well-known data scientist and deevloper. Check out his site here, http://hadley.nz/. Once there, take a look around and even check out some of the other amazing packages he’s created! Some of these include: tidyr, dplyr, stringr, and many more! Some of these we’re going to talk about in depth in other tutorials, but for now, back to ggplot2!

Why ggplot2?

Although base R comes with solid visualizations capabilities, it’s really hard to beat what ggplot2 brings to the table. Not only is using ggplot2 extremely straightforward (after some practice), but the end result is almost always more aesthetically pleasing than what could be produced through base R graphics. Before I explain more about ggplot2, let’s look at a graphic made using it.

Here’s one using the diamonds dataset that comes with ggplot2:

Although there is a lot going on in this visualization, we can see clearly an exponential increase in the price of a diamond based on its carat size. However, this graphic extends this analysis one step further and provides a color representation for each clarity classification. Using this additional layer, we can see that some depending on the clarity classification, the price of a diamond increases faster based on changes in the carat size.

Okay, so this graphic is pretty cool, but it’s also extremely basic. In fact, it only took one line of code to make:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price, col = clarity)) + geom_point(alpha = .2)

This is your first glimpse at what the syntax for a ggplot2 visualization looks like. Don’t worry about what’s actually happening here, just notice how simple it was to create the above plot. But what makes ggplot2 so simple? When creating the package, Hadley Wickham decided to build it upon the foundations of the grammar of graphics. Before we can truly understand the power and simplicity of ggplot2, we must understand the basics of the grammar of graphics; which is where the gg in ggplot2 comes from.
